DTSTAMP:20260309T092238Z
DESCRIPTION:Event Types: Arts\,Community\,Special Events<br>Neighborhood
 s: Citywide\,Pioneer Square<br>Sponsoring Organization: Town Hall Seattl
 e<br>Contact: Rana San<br>Contact Phone: (206) 256-6279<br>Contact Email
 : Rana.San@seattle.gov<br>Audience: All<br>Pre-Register: No<br>Cost: Fre
 e<br>Link: https://townhallseattle.org/event/this-art-here/<br><br><p>Wh
 at roles do artists play in civil society? What do artists think about w
 hen they think about making things in public? Is art a basic need? Join 
 us in conversation with Nakisa Dehpanah\, Titus Ross\, and Imani Sims&#8
 212\;three artists pushing towards a future rooted in collaboration\, re
 silience\, and transformation.<br><br>Each artist is part of the Seattle
  Office of Arts &amp\; Culture&#8217\;s collective imagining\, &#8220\;W
 e Still Dream a Future&#8221\;. This series features more than thirty ar
 tists and artist groups performing\, dancing\, installing\, learning\, o
 rganizing\, and exhibiting around Downtown\, the C-ID\, Pioneer Square\,
  Stadium District\, Union and King Street Stations this year.<br><br>The
  conversation will be hosted by Matthew Offenbacher\, Seattle artist and
  advisor for ARTS at King Street Station.<br><br>This program is support
 ed by the City of Seattle Office of Arts &amp\; Culture and is part of t
 he commUNITY series\, a selection of free public programs that center co
 nnection\, career development\, and the co-creation of art curated by&#1
 60\;ARTS at King Street Station Advisors.&#160\;</p><hr><p><strong>About
  the artists</strong>:<br><strong>Nakisa Dehpanah</strong> explores the 
 relationship between the body and imposed structures&#8212\;political\, 
 spatial\, and cultural&#8212\;through sculptural installation and video.
  Using textile-based forms and movement documentation\, the work examine
 s how displacement shapes memory and belonging\, tracing the body&#39\;s
  capacity to adapt\, resist\, and transform across different environment
 s and lived experiences.<br><br><strong>Titus Ross</strong> is a Seattle
 -based fashion designer\, creative director\, and founder of thirty+. A 
 self-taught artist\, he began creating with whatever resources he could 
 find\, shaping a vision that now reaches audiences across the U.S.\, the
  UK\, China\, France\, and Africa. His work transforms discarded materia
 ls into garments that carry stories of resilience\, identity\, and commu
 nity. Runways for Ross are never just about clothes&#8212\;they&#8217\;r
 e living spaces where music\, performance\, and fashion collide to spark
  dialogue and connection. Projects like Grassroots and PNW Fashion Week:
  Sustainability Matters reflect his belief that fashion can be both sust
 ainable and deeply inclusive. For Ross\, fashion is more than clothes&#8
 212\;it&#8217\;s a movement\, a safe space\, and a chance to reimagine w
 hat we leave behind and what we carry forward.<br><br><strong>Imani Sims
 </strong> is an alchemist and author from Seattle\, WA. Wonder is Imani&
 #8217\;s specialty and drawing inspiration from the cosmos to integrate 
 art\, ritual\, and the Black aesthetic into experiences tailored for QTB
 IPOC communities and allies. With a background spanning over three decad
 es in performance &amp\; literature\, they&#8217\;ve dedicated themselve
 s to fostering spaces where imagination thrives. Their shelves overflow 
 with books delving into Afrofuturist realms\, and their tarot deck\, The
  Deck of N0NE\, embodies their deep connection to the genre. Imani&#8217
 \;s work is a world within a world. Find Imani on Instagram @bookthirtyt
 hree &amp\; <a href="https://protect2.fireeye.com/v1/url?k=31323334-50bb
 a2bf-31321b84-4544474f5631-e252c97ba796ec54&amp\;q=1&amp\;e=a71d4ed8-45d
 e-496b-a0d7-c1e6d7a2cb28&amp\;u=http%3A%2F%2Fwwww.thedeckofnone.com%2F" 
 target="_blank" rel="noopener">wwww.thedeckofnone.com</a><br><br><strong
 >About the host:<br>Matthew Offenbacher</strong> is a long-time Seattle 
 artist and community organizer. His work has been called &#8220\;freakis
 hly egoless\,&#8221\; vulnerable\, funny and queer. Over the past severa
 l years\, he has made an installation of protection charms in I-5 Colonn
 ade Park\, a painting installation with four dancers\, a musician and a 
 bystander intervention trainer\, and a giant walk-in fish belly made of 
 PVC pipe that was also a percussion instrument and temporary performance
  space.<br><br><strong>About the series</strong>:<br>The <a href="https:
 //artbeat.seattle.gov/2025/10/22/community-fall-lineup/" target="_blank"
  rel="noopener"><strong>commUNITY series</strong></a> is a selection of 
 free public programs that center connection\, career development\, and t
 he co-creation of art. Curated by&#160\;<a href="https://www.seattle.gov
 /arts/programs/arts-at-king-street-station#about" target="_blank" rel="n
 oopener">ARTS at King Street Station Advisors</a>\, this series brings t
 ogether their visions and talents to build community\, engage attendees 
 in powerful arts practices\, and offer free career development and skill
 -building for all ages. This series features workshops by Ashanti Davis
 \, Alicia Mullikin\, Shaudi Vahdat\, Scott Oshima\, and Marie Kidhe.</p>
CATEGORIES:Arts and Culture
